# GPUI Patterns for u-forge.ai

Hard-won lessons from building the Alpha desktop UI on GPUI 0.2.2 (crates.io, blade-graphics backend). Violating these causes subtle bugs, silent regressions, or hard-to-diagnose perf spikes.

**Stay on `gpui = "0.2.2"`.** Zed `main` has restructured into
`gpui_platform`/`gpui_linux`/`gpui_wgpu` sub-crates with a different entry
point; upgrading requires a targeted API compatibility pass.

---

## Render phases — the critical invariant

GPUI processes each frame in three sequential phases: `request_layout` → `prepaint` → `paint`.

**Never mutate view state or call `cx.notify()` from inside a `canvas` paint closure or from `paint`.** This re-invalidates the frame you just finished and doubles cost per frame. Size-affecting work belongs in `request_layout`.

This was the root cause of the reverted paint-time shape-cache: moving text shaping into `paint` with a cross-frame `WrappedLine` cache caused measured height to differ from the pre-paint guess, triggering `cx.notify()` and a double-pass on every frame. A paint-phase cache cannot beat a layout-phase non-cache unless it avoids the notify cascade.

---

## `AnyView::cached()` — view-level caching

Wrap heavy sub-views that re-lay-out on every root-view notify with:

```rust
AnyView::from(entity).cached(StyleRefinement::default().size_full())
```

How it works (`gpui-0.2.2` `AnyView::prepaint`): stores `bounds`, `content_mask`, and `text_style` as a cache key. On the next frame, if all three match AND `window.dirty_views` does NOT contain this entity's id AND `window.refreshing == false`, GPUI calls `reuse_prepaint()` / `reuse_paint()` — the subtree's `render()`, layout, and paint are **all skipped**.

`cx.notify()` **only marks the calling entity** — children are not transitively dirtied. So dragging a sidebar handle notifies `AppView` only; `ChatPanel` is not in `dirty_views` and its `.cached()` hits. Streaming a token notifies one `ChatMessageView`; other panels stay clean.

`window.refresh()` bypasses `.cached()` entirely and forces everything to re-render. Do not call it unless you mean it.

**Required invariant:** the cache-key (bounds) must be stable for the frames you want to be free. If the outer container changes width (e.g. `w(0.)` ↔ `w(400.)` on toggle), bounds change and the cache misses — paying full cold-mount cost on every toggle.

`.cached()` lives on `AnyView`, not `Entity<V>`. Use `AnyView::from(entity).cached(...)` or `entity.to_any().cached(...)`.

---

## Always-mounted panel pattern

The companion to `.cached()`. Do NOT use `if panel_open { body.child(panel) }` — removing an element from the tree for a frame GC's its element_state including the `.cached()` key, so the next mount is cold.

Instead, keep the panel always in the tree and vary only the **outer** container's visible width:

```rust
// Outer: variable width, overflow_hidden, relative (anchor for absolute child).
div()
    .relative().flex_none()
    .w(px(if open { width } else { 0.0 }))
    .h_full()
    .overflow_hidden()
    .child(
        // Inner: fixed width always, absolute-positioned so it escapes the
        // outer's layout constraint. Clipped to 0px by overflow_hidden when closed.
        div()
            .absolute().top_0().left_0()
            .w(px(width)).h_full().overflow_hidden()
            .child(
                AnyView::from(panel.clone())
                    .cached(StyleRefinement::default().size_full()),
            ),
    )
```

The inner absolute-positioned div gives the cached view stable bounds; the outer width controls visibility via clipping. Toggle is a cache-hit. Resize still invalidates (correct — user sees the resize).

Applied to `ChatPanel` in `app_view/render.rs`. Apply to any future heavy-to-layout side panel.

