## GPUI layout constraints

Required for scroll areas to work correctly inside a flex layout:

- **`overflow_hidden()` on the body container** — without this, flex children that render more content than their computed size grow the parent rather than clip.
- **`min_h_0()` on flex children with scrollable content** — flex items default to `min-height: auto`, preventing them from shrinking below content height. `min_h_0()` overrides this so the item can shrink to its flex-allocated size and let the inner `overflow_y_scroll()` div take over.
- **Separate shell div from scroll area div** — outer div (`flex_col`, `flex_none` width, `min_h_0()`) provides the fixed size; inner div (`overflow_y_scroll()`, `flex_grow`) holds scrollable content. Combining them on one div causes layout issues.
- **`WeakEntity<T>` for drag callbacks** — `on_drag_move` and `on_click` closures receive `&mut App` (no `Context<V>`). Capture `cx.weak_entity()` before building the element tree, then call `handle.update(cx, |view, cx| { … })` inside the closure. This is the correct GPUI 0.2.2 pattern when `cx.listener()` isn't available.

---

## Frame-cost profiling

Do not trust how often `render()` is called — that measures re-render frequency, not actual frame cost. To measure real frame time (tree build + layout + paint), append a 1×1 `canvas` element whose paint closure records `frame_start.elapsed()` into entity state. The canvas fires after GPUI has completed layout, so it captures the true per-frame cost.

`AppView` has a built-in perf overlay toggled by `Ctrl+Shift+P` (or the "Perf" button in the status bar), showing `frame:<ms>  avg:<60-frame>  chat:<chat_ms>`. Enable it before guessing at a UI slowdown. See `app_view/render.rs` — the timing canvas is the last element in the tree.

The 60-frame average uses `FrameTimeRing` (`[u64; 60]` circular buffer in `app_view/state.rs`); sampling and averaging are both gated on `perf_enabled` so a disabled overlay does zero work beyond the enable check.
